    {
      "id": 127,
      "title": "LLM Router — Core Architecture",
      "status": "pending",
      "priority": "high",
      "dependencies": [],
      "details": "Design and implement a dynamic LLM routing layer for the bot that intelligently selects the optimal backend based on multiple real-time signals including time-of-day, prompt complexity analysis, current GPU load, LAN latency measurements, and explicit user overrides. The router must integrate tightly with the existing CPU pipeline as a pre-LLM decision layer, receiving context from the prompt preprocessor and returning a selected backend plus routing metadata before any model invocation occurs.\n\nDefine the core RoutingContext struct that encapsulates all decision inputs: timestamp, prompt tokens, estimated complexity score, current GPU utilization, measured LAN RTT to remote nodes, user-specified backend preference, and session history flags. Define the LLMBackend enum with variants for Grok, Gemini, local RTX 3090, LAN Ollama clusters, and future cloud providers, each carrying associated metadata such as endpoint, cost tier, and capability tags.\n\nImplement the pure routing function that takes RoutingContext and returns a deterministic BackendSelection result. The function must be side-effect free, easily unit-testable, and support pluggable strategy modules. Plan for future backends by making the enum and selection logic extensible without core changes.\n\nAdd config-driven thresholds for complexity cutoffs, GPU load percentages, and time-of-day windows that can be hot-reloaded. Ensure full compatibility with the existing tool, skill, and hook system so routing decisions can be observed or overridden by hooks. Implement comprehensive logging and telemetry that records every routing decision with full context, latency, and outcome for later analysis.\n\nDesign fallback logic that gracefully degrades to the next viable backend when the primary selection is unavailable due to connectivity, quota, or hardware issues, while still respecting user overrides where possible. The entire router must remain deterministic for reproducibility, modular for testing, and observable for debugging.",
      "testStrategy": "Unit tests covering all branches of the pure routing function with mocked RoutingContext inputs for time-of-day, complexity, load, and latency combinations. Property-based tests to verify determinism and that no invalid backend is ever returned. Integration tests that exercise the router inside the CPU pipeline with real prompt samples and simulated telemetry hooks. Simulated load tests using synthetic GPU/latency traces to validate threshold behavior and fallback paths under high contention. Add golden-file tests for routing decisions under fixed config thresholds to prevent regressions.",
      "subtasks": [
        {
          "id": "127.1",
          "title": "Define RoutingContext struct and LLMBackend enum",
          "status": "pending",
          "details": "Create the Rust structs and enums with serde support and documentation.",
        },
        {
          "id": "127.2",
          "title": "Implement pure routing function",
          "status": "pending",
          "details": "Write the core deterministic selection logic with strategy trait.",
        },
        {
          "id": "127.3",
          "title": "Add config-driven thresholds and time windows (12hr format)",
          "status": "pending",
          "details": "Implement TOML/JSON config loading with hot-reload support.",
        },
        {
          "id": "127.4",
          "title": "Integrate router into CPU pipeline",
          "status": "pending",
          "details": "Wire the pre-LLM decision layer and pass context correctly.",
        },
        {
          "id": "127.5",
          "title": "Implement logging and telemetry",
          "status": "pending",
          "details": "Add structured logging and metrics emission for every decision.",
        },
        {
          "id": "127.6",
          "title": "Build fallback and error handling logic",
          "status": "pending",
          "details": "Create resilient fallback chain with user override precedence.",
        },
        {
          "id": "127.7",
